		<div id="siteNotice"><script type='text/javascript'>if (wgNotice != '') document.writeln(wgNotice);</script></div>		<h1 id="firstHeading" class="firstHeading">Etiquette</h1>
		<div id="bodyContent">
			<h3 id="siteSub">From Wikipedia, the free encyclopedia</h3>
			<div id="contentSub"></div>
									<div id="jump-to-nav">Jump to: <a href="#column-one">navigation</a>, <a href="#searchInput">search</a></div>			<!-- start content -->
			<div class="dablink">For other uses, see <a href="/wiki/Etiquette_(disambiguation)" title="Etiquette (disambiguation)">Etiquette (disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:182px;"><a href="/wiki/File:High-Change-in-Bond-Street-Gillray.jpeg" class="image" title="In High-Change in Bond Street,—ou—la Politesse du Grande Monde (1796), James Gillray caricatured the lack of etiquette in a group of men leering at women and crowding them off a sidewalk."><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/81/High-Change-in-Bond-Street-Gillray.jpeg/180px-High-Change-in-Bond-Street-Gillray.jpeg" width="180" height="129" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:High-Change-in-Bond-Street-Gillray.jpeg" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
In <i>High-Change in Bond Street,—ou—la Politesse du Grande Monde</i> (1796), <a href="/wiki/James_Gillray" title="James Gillray">James Gillray</a> caricatured the lack of etiquette in a group of men leering at women and crowding them off a sidewalk.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><b>Etiquette</b> is a code that influences expectations for <a href="/wiki/Social_behavior" title="Social behavior">social behavior</a> according to contemporary <a href="/wiki/Convention_(norm)" title="Convention (norm)">conventional</a> <a href="/wiki/Norm_(sociology)" title="Norm (sociology)">norms</a> within a <a href="/wiki/Society" title="Society">society</a>, <a href="/wiki/Social_class" title="Social class">social class</a>, or <a href="/wiki/Group_(sociology)" title="Group (sociology)" class="mw-redirect">group</a>. Rules of etiquette are usually unwritten, but aspects of etiquette have been codified from time to time. Rules of etiquette encompass most aspects of social interaction in any society, though the term itself is not commonly used. A rule of etiquette may reflect an underlying <a href="/wiki/Ethical_code" title="Ethical code">ethical code</a>, or it may reflect a person's <a href="/wiki/Fashion" title="Fashion">fashion</a> or <a href="/wiki/Status" title="Status">status</a>.</p>
<p>Like "<a href="/wiki/Culture" title="Culture">culture</a>", it is a word that has gradually grown plural, especially in a <a href="/wiki/Multi-ethnic_society" title="Multi-ethnic society" class="mw-redirect">multi-ethnic society</a> with many clashing expectations. Thus, it is now possible to refer to "an etiquette" or "a culture", realizing that these may not be universal. In Britain, though, the word etiquette has its roots in the eighteenth century, becoming a universal force in the nineteenth century to the extent that it has been described as the one word that aptly describes life during <a href="/wiki/Victorian_era" title="Victorian era">the reign of Queen Victoria</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
